Also, your own example can't be used in the current scope of discussion because you were raised in USA as you said but born to Indian family. You were exposed to the tones, accents of which ever regional language your parents or family speaks at a much tender age and that would have helped you to have a more balanced accent. But that is not the case in majority of the Indian families where most of the interaction happens in regional languages and English is either spoken in schools/colleges/friends circle. People develop their English accent that has impressions of their specific cultural, regional and social marking. Further to this they are raised in that set-up for a substantial phase of their impressionable age until 18-20 years. One can't go to a foreign country and start speaking in say native Irish accent, it just doesn't work like that. 
All these use-cases and complexities are explained in the paper that was shared.
